phase 1: data preprocessing¶

Problems with Unbalanced Data in Clustering¶

Imbalance in the data can cause problems in the sorting process. In cases where the number of samples are from heterogeneous categories, clustering algorithms may pay more attention to samples from larger categories and ignore samples from smaller categories. This may cause clusters of unsustainable sizes and be careful to reduce them.

  • The model might focus on the dominant class, and the minority classes may be poorly represented in the resulting clusters.
  • If the number of samples of one category is much less than the other categories, the model may prefer towards larger categories and this will cause bias in the model.

Solutions for Handling Unbalanced Data in Clustering:¶

  • Assign weights to different instances or clusters based on their class frequencies.
  • Use oversampling (increasing the number of instances in the minority class) or undersampling (reducing the number of instances in the majority class) to balance the class distribution.

def preprocess_text(text):
    tokenizer = Tokenizer()
    tokens = tokenizer.tokenize_words(text)
    
    normalizer = Normalizer()
    normalized_tokens = [normalizer.normalize(token) for token in tokens]
    
    stemmer = FindStems()
    stemmed_tokens = [stemmer.convert_to_stem(token) for token in normalized_tokens]
    
    normalized_text = ' '.join(stemmed_tokens)
    
    return normalized_text
In [4]:
def preprocess_text_with_stopwords(text):
    tokenizer = Tokenizer()
    tokens = tokenizer.tokenize_words(text)
    
    normalizer = Normalizer()
    normalized_tokens = [normalizer.normalize(token) for token in tokens]
    
    tokens_without_stopwords = [token for token in normalized_tokens if token not in persian_stopwords]
    
    stemmer = FindStems()
    stemmed_tokens = [stemmer.convert_to_stem(token) for token in tokens_without_stopwords]
    
    normalized_text = ' '.join(stemmed_tokens)
    
    return normalized_text

stemming or lemmatization¶

Stemming:¶

  • Stemming involves removing prefixes or suffixes from words to obtain their root form. The result (stem) may not necessarily be a valid word, but it aims to capture the core meaning of related words.
  • Stemming is useful when the goal is to reduce words to a common base form, ignoring language semantics.
  • for example:
    • Original: "running," "runner," "ran"
    • Stemmed: "run"

Lemmatization:¶

  • Lemmatization involves reducing words to their base or dictionary form (lemma). Unlike stemming, lemmatization ensures that the resulting word is valid in the language.
  • Lemmatization typically involves using a lexicon and morphological analysis to determine the base form of a word.
  • It considers the part-of-speech (POS) of the word to generate the correct lemma.
  • for example:
    • Original: "running," "runner," "ran"
    • Lemmatized: "run"

Choosing between Stemming and Lemmatization:¶

  • Stemming is suitable for times when processing speed is important and high accuracy is not required.
  • Lemmatization is suitable for cases where we need more precision in retrieving the meaning of words.

train_data = pd.read_csv('preprocessed_train_data.csv', encoding='utf-8')

train_data['preprocessed_content'] = train_data['preprocessed_content'].fillna('')

tokenized_data = [text.split() for text in train_data['preprocessed_content']]

tagged_data = [TaggedDocument(words=doc, tags=[str(i)]) for i, doc in enumerate(tokenized_data)]

model = Doc2Vec(vector_size=100, window=5, min_count=1, workers=4, epochs=20)
model.build_vocab(tagged_data)
model.train(tagged_data, total_examples=model.corpus_count, epochs=model.epochs)

model.save('doc2vec_model')

model = Doc2Vec.load('doc2vec_model')

3.feature vector:¶

Representation of Data:¶

  • Feature vectors serve as a compact and numerical representation of data points. They capture the essential characteristics of the data in a structured format.
  • Features are the individual dimensions or attributes of the data that contribute to forming the feature vector.

Dimensionality Reduction:¶

  • Feature vectors often serve as a means of reducing the dimensionality of the data. Instead of working with the original, potentially high-dimensional data, algorithms operate on feature vectors with a reduced number of dimensions.
  • Dimensionality reduction can be crucial for computational efficiency and for avoiding the curse of dimensionality.

Compatibility with Machine Learning Libraries:¶

  • Most machine learning libraries, including scikit-learn, TensorFlow, and PyTorch, expect input data in the form of feature vectors. Adhering to this standard allows for seamless integration with widely-used tools and libraries.

4.Explain of word2vec and doc2vec:¶

Word2Vec:¶

  • Word Embedding: Learns continuous vector representations for words.
  • Skip-gram and CBOW: Two architectures for predicting context words given a target word or vice versa.
  • Training Process: Adjusts word vectors to maximize the likelihood of predicting context words based on co-occurrence patterns.
  • Vector Representation: Each word is represented by a dense vector capturing semantic relationships.

Doc2Vec:¶

  • Paragraph Vector (Doc2Vec): Extends Word2Vec to represent entire documents.
  • DM and DBOW: Two architectures for predicting words or context in documents.
  • Training Process: Adjusts vectors to maximize the likelihood of predicting words or context in the training data.
  • Vector Representation: Each document is represented by a vector capturing its overall context and semantic relationships.

5.Pros and conse of DBSCAN and K-means :¶

k_MEAN:¶

  • Choose K initial cluster centroids randomly or using a specific initialization method.
  • Assign each data point to the nearest centroid, forming K clusters.
  • Recalculate the centroids of each cluster based on the mean of the assigned points.
  • Iterate between assignment and centroid update until convergence or a specified number of iterations.
  • Advantages:
    • Simplicity: Simple and easy to implement.
    • Efficiency: Computationally efficient, especially for large datasets.
    • Scalability: Scales well with the number of data points.
  • Disadvantages:
    • Sensitive to Initialization: Results can vary based on initial centroid placement.
    • Assumes Equal Variance: Assumes that clusters have similar variances, which may not be true for all datasets.
    • Requires Specifying K: The number of clusters (K) needs to be specified in advance.

DBSCAN:¶

  • Identify core points that have a minimum number of points (MinPts) within a specified radius (Eps).
  • Form clusters by connecting core points that are within each other's radius.
  • Assign non-core points that are within the radius of a core point to the corresponding cluster.
  • Points that do not belong to any cluster are considered noise.
  • Advantages:
    • Handles Irregular Shapes: Can find clusters with irregular shapes and handle varying cluster densities.
    • No Need to Specify K: Automatically determines the number of clusters based on data density.
    • Robust to Outliers: Outliers do not affect the clustering significantly.
  • Disadvantages:
    • Sensitive to Parameters: Sensitive to the choice of parameters (Eps and MinPts).
    • Not Deterministic: Results can vary based on the order of processing points.

Comparison:¶

  • K-Means is Parametric: Requires specifying the number of clusters (K) in advance, while DBSCAN is non-parametric and automatically determines the number of clusters.
  • Shape of Clusters: K-Means assumes spherical clusters and may struggle with irregular shapes, while DBSCAN can find clusters with various shapes.
  • Handling Noise: DBSCAN is robust to noise and outliers, while K-Means is sensitive to outliers.
  • Computational Complexity: K-Means is computationally efficient and scales well, whereas DBSCAN can be more computationally intensive, especially in high-dimensional spaces.

PCA (Principal Component Analysis):¶

PCA is a dimensionality reduction technique used to transform high-dimensional data into a lower-dimensional representation. It achieves this by identifying and extracting the most important features, called principal components, that capture the maximum variance in the data.

  • Subtract the mean of each feature from every data point to center the data around the origin.
  • Compute the covariance matrix to capture relationships between different features.
  • Perform eigendecomposition on the covariance matrix to obtain eigenvectors and eigenvalues.
  • Rank eigenvectors by their corresponding eigenvalues.
  • Choose the top eigenvectors as principal components, representing new axes in the transformed space.
  • Project the original data onto the selected principal components to create a lower-dimensional representation.

Evaluation and analysis¶

Silhouette Score:¶

The silhouette score is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster (cohesion) compared to other clusters (separation). It ranges from -1 to 1, where a high value indicates well-defined clusters.

  • Calculate Cohesion (a):
    • For each data point, calculate the average distance to all other points in the same cluster. This represents how close the point is to the other points in its cluster.
  • Calculate Separation (b):
    • For each data point, calculate the average distance to all points in the nearest cluster (different from the one the point belongs to). This represents how far the point is from points in the nearest other cluster.
  • Calculate Silhouette Score (s):
    • For each data point, calculate the silhouette score using the formula: S = (b-a)/max(a,b)
    • Average the silhouette scores for all data points to get the overall score.

Homogeneity Score:¶

The homogeneity score measures the extent to which each cluster contains only members of a single class. It ranges from 0 to 1, where 1 indicates perfect homogeneity.

  • ontingency Table:
    • Create a contingency table that represents the true class labels versus the assigned cluster labels.
  • Calculate Homogeneity Score:
    • Use the contingency table to calculate the homogeneity score using the formula: H = 1 - (H(C|K)/H(C))
    • where H(C∣K) is the conditional entropy of the true classes given the assigned clusters, and H(C) is the entropy of the true classes.

solutions to improve the performance¶

  • Feature Scaling:
    • Ensure that your features are on the same scale. Use techniques like Min-Max scaling or Standardization (Z-score normalization) to make sure features contribute equally to the distance computations.
  • Optimal Parameter Selection:
    • Tune the hyperparameters of your clustering algorithms. For example, in K-Means, experiment with different values of 'k' (number of clusters). In DBSCAN, adjust the 'eps' (radius) and 'min_samples' parameters.
  • Dimensionality Reduction:
    • Apply dimensionality reduction techniques such as PCA before clustering. Reducing the number of dimensions can help focus on the most important features and improve algorithm performance.
  • Data Preprocessing:
    • Clean and preprocess the data effectively. Handle missing values, outliers, and noisy data appropriately. Ensure that the data is in a suitable format for clustering.
